claims:
Claims 1. A method of generating a high dynamic range video from a sensor having an adjustable gain value, the method comprising: a. setting a frame rate that defines a frame period; b. setting a subframe number per frame; c. setting a plurality of exposure periods for each subframe based on the frame period and the subframe number such that a summation of the exposure periods in the plurality is less than or equal to the frame period; d. setting a plurality of gain values, one for each subframe, wherein the plurality has at least two different values; e. capturing a plurality of subframe images from the sensor, wherein each in the plurality of subframe images is captured based on one from the plurality of exposure periods and one from the plurality of gain values; f. compositing the plurality of subframe images into a composite frame image; g. repeating steps (e) and (f) to generate a plurality of composite frame images; h. creating the high dynamic range video based on the plurality of composite frame images; and i. providing a light source and activating the light source prior to step (e), then deactivating the light source after step (e). 2. The method of claim 1, wherein the exposure period for each subframe is constant. 3. The method of claim 2, wherein the subframe number is 3, and the plurality of gain values comprises three different gain values. 4. The method of claim 1, wherein the exposure period for each subframe is variable. 5. The method of claim 1, wherein the subframe number is 3, and the plurality of exposure periods comprises a long, a medium, and a short exposure period, and the plurality of gain values comprises a high, a medium, and a low gain value, wherein: 

 the subframe with the long exposure period comprises the high gain value; the subframe with the medium exposure period comprises the medium gain value; and the subframe with the short exposure period comprises the low gain value. 6. The method of claim 1, wherein an exposure value (EV) for a first subframe is different from an EV for a second subframe, wherein the EV is based on the product of the subframe exposure period and the subframe gain value. 7. A high dynamic range video system comprising: a sensor having an adjustable gain value; a light source; a processor connected to the sensor and light source, where the processor is configured to perform the following steps of: a. setting a frame rate that defines a frame period; b. setting a subframe number per frame; c. setting a plurality of exposure periods for each subframe based on the frame period and subframe number such that a summation of the exposure periods in the plurality is less than or equal to the frame period; d. setting a plurality of gain values, one for each subframe, wherein the plurality has at least two different values; e. capturing a plurality of subframe images from the sensor, wherein each in the plurality of subframe images is captured based on one from the plurality of exposure periods and one from the plurality of gain values; f. compositing the plurality of subframe images into a composite frame image; g. repeating steps (e) and (f) to generate a plurality of composite frame images; h. creating the high dynamic range video based on the plurality of composite frame images; and i. activating the light source prior to step (e), then deactivating the light source after step (e). 8. The system of claim 7, wherein the processor is further configured to deactivate the sensor. 9. The system of claim 7, wherein the exposure period for each subframe is constant. 10. The system of claim 9, wherein the subframe number is 3, and the plurality of gain values comprises three different gain values. 11. The system of claim 7, wherein the exposure period for each subframe is variable. 12. The system of claim 7, wherein the subframe number is 3, and the plurality of exposure periods comprises a long, a medium, and a short exposure period, and the plurality of gain values comprises a high, a medium, and a low gain value, wherein: the subframe with the long exposure period comprises the high gain value; the subframe with the medium exposure period comprises the medium gain value; and the subframe with the short exposure period comprises the low gain value. 13. The system of claim 7, wherein an exposure value (EV) for a first subframe is different from an EV for a second subframe, wherein the EV is based on the product of the subframe exposure period and the subframe gain value. 14. A system for determining the particle sizes within a colloid, the system comprising: a light source constructed to direct a beam of electromagnetic radiation at a specimen chamber constructed to allow a portion of the beam to scatter when illuminating particles within the chamber, wherein the light source is configured to frequently change the amount of electromagnetic radiation that reaches the specimen chamber in a frame period from a first amount to a second amount, wherein the frequency of change is based on the frame rate; 

 a sensor positioned to detect the scatter of the beam, the sensor having a frame rate; and a processor connected to the light source and to the sensor, the processor configured to perform the following steps: A. activating the light source; B. capturing a plurality of images from the sensor; C. segregating a plurality of images into a first set of images corresponding to the images captured when the specimen chamber is exposed to the first amount of electromagnetic radiation; and D. segregating a plurality of images into a second set of images corresponding to the images captured when the specimen chamber is exposed to the second amount of electromagnetic radiation. 15. The system of claim 14, wherein the processor additionally performs the following steps: E. finding and tracking particles based on the first set of images; F. finding and tracking particles based on the second set of images. 16. The system of claim 15, wherein the processor determines the sizes of the particles based on steps (E) and (F). 17. The system of claim 14, further comprising an imaging objective that focuses the scattered portion of the beam onto the sensor. 18. The system of claim 14, wherein the sensor is a black and white camera. 19. The system of claim 14, wherein the light source is a laser. 20. The system of claim 14, further comprising a light sheet former that forms the beams into a sheet of electromagnetic radiation directed at the specimen chamber. 21. The system of claim 14, wherein the light source is further configured to frequently change the amount of electromagnetic radiation that reaches the specimen chamber from the first amount to the second amount and to a third amount, wherein the frequency of change is based on the frame rate; and wherein the processor is further configured to perform the steps of: segregating a plurality of images into a third set of images corresponding to the images captured when the specimen chamber is exposed to the third amount of electromagnetic radiation; and finding and tracking particles based on the third set of images. 22. The system of claim 14, further comprising: an optical chopper positioned between the specimen chamber and the light source, the optical chopper comprising: a rotation structure adapted to rotate, comprising a first filter that permits transmission of the first amount of electromagnetic radiation and a second filter that permits transmission of the second amount of electromagnetic radiation; a motor adapted to rotate the rotation structure; a synchronization mark or structure constructed to indicate the rotational position of the rotation structure; wherein, as the rotation structure rotates, the beam of electromagnetic radiation alternates between passing through the first filter and the second filter; and a detector constructed to detect the position of the synchronization mark or structure; wherein the processor is connected to the detector and to the optical chopper, and wherein the processor is further configured to perform the following steps: activating the motor; detecting the synchronization mark or structure; and 

